WEBVTT

01:27.120 --> 01:30.000
I'm looking for Dr Westphall.
He's expecting me.

01:30.000 --> 01:33.760
Down the hall, that way.
Second door on the left.

01:33.760 --> 01:37.760
            Thank you.

01:43.080 --> 01:44.000
KNOCKING

01:44.000 --> 01:48.000
KNOCKING
Come in.

01:48.480 --> 01:52.480
George.

01:52.640 --> 01:54.800
Here I am.
Back in the house McCabe built.

01:54.800 --> 01:56.080
You look great.

01:56.080 --> 01:57.800
               Ryan.

01:57.800 --> 02:01.800
This is Dr Westphall. He and I were
best friends when we were growing up.

02:02.080 --> 02:03.600
       I'm worried, Donald.

02:03.600 --> 02:06.320
Ryan's been feeling lousy
the last couple of weeks.

02:06.320 --> 02:09.120
Coughing, peeing a lot, out of sorts.

02:09.120 --> 02:11.760
I know, I talked briefly
     with your doctor.

02:11.760 --> 02:14.480
Let's have a look at you, pal.
Feeling a little punk, are we?

02:14.480 --> 02:18.480
A little.

02:20.520 --> 02:22.200
Open your mouth, will you?

02:22.200 --> 02:25.480
Are you thirsty all the time?

02:25.480 --> 02:28.680
OK, well let's check you in
and do some tests, all right?

02:28.680 --> 02:32.680
Don't worry, George.

02:33.040 --> 02:34.600
Have a seat.

02:34.600 --> 02:37.280
Somebody will be down to get you.
Eventually.

02:37.280 --> 02:39.960
Why don't you just put
that speech on tape?

02:39.960 --> 02:42.160
What are you up to anyway?

02:42.160 --> 02:44.000
             59, 170.

02:44.000 --> 02:47.160
This the kind of material you
were doing before you got shot?

02:47.160 --> 02:49.720
Drug centre rehabbed
your sense of humour too.

02:49.720 --> 02:52.720
Off the dope,
back to the old Julie McPhail.

02:52.720 --> 02:55.160
I thought you were
getting patient histories.

02:55.160 --> 02:57.600
This looks like a
college transcript.

02:57.600 --> 02:59.400
This looks like a
college transcript.
               Shhh.

02:59.400 --> 03:00.520
Can you keep a secret?

03:00.520 --> 03:01.000
Can you keep a secret?
                No.

03:01.000 --> 03:02.320
Can you keep a secret?
                No.
I'll tell you anyway.

03:02.320 --> 03:06.160
I'm changing a grade. I got an
incomplete in Kilroy's English class.

03:06.160 --> 03:09.640
You've been out of school for ten
years. You've got a medical degree.

03:09.640 --> 03:11.840
What the hell's the difference?

03:11.840 --> 03:15.240
Ever since my near-demise,
I've been tying up some loose ends,

03:15.240 --> 03:16.840
     and the occasional nurse.

03:16.840 --> 03:20.840
This scarlet I has been gnawing
at my craw for the last few years.

03:21.560 --> 03:24.440
           Not any more.

03:24.440 --> 03:25.960
Excuse me.

03:25.960 --> 03:28.000
What can I do for you?

03:28.000 --> 03:29.200
What can I do for you?
I'm in labour.

03:29.200 --> 03:31.120
I'm in management.

03:31.120 --> 03:32.760
Could you tell Dr Morrison I'm here?

03:32.760 --> 03:36.760
Mrs Tillman. Melissa Tillman.

03:36.960 --> 03:40.880
Could you page Dr Morrison
to admitting?

03:40.880 --> 03:41.760
              Hello.

03:41.760 --> 03:44.600
              Hello.
Hi.

03:44.600 --> 03:48.440
Ooh, I think I'd better sit down.

03:48.440 --> 03:51.400
Get her upstairs stat and be
sure she's well taken care of.

03:51.400 --> 03:53.440
Why? What's it to you?

03:53.440 --> 03:57.440
   That woman's having my baby.

04:03.440 --> 04:07.440
OK, hop out.

04:08.440 --> 04:11.200
These are yours. Put them on.
Do you want some help?

04:11.200 --> 04:12.240
No.

04:12.240 --> 04:15.480
OK, I'll be back in a
while to take some blood.

04:15.480 --> 04:19.480
From your neck.

04:25.480 --> 04:29.360
A little old, but I'd do that.
I'd do that in a second.

04:29.360 --> 04:31.080
         Bring any comics?

04:31.080 --> 04:32.280
No.

04:32.280 --> 04:34.040
Useless.

04:34.040 --> 04:35.920
Any hot-looking sisters
gonna be visiting?

04:35.920 --> 04:38.240
All mine are ugly.

04:38.240 --> 04:40.360
   Shame. What's wrong with you?

04:40.360 --> 04:41.720
   Shame. What's wrong with you?
Don't know.

04:41.720 --> 04:45.120
Ditto.
Something in my arm.

04:45.120 --> 04:47.920
They're slicing Marcus open tomorrow.

04:47.920 --> 04:49.560
Heart surgery.
Imagine that.

04:49.560 --> 04:51.120
Some doc touching your bare heart.

04:51.120 --> 04:52.120
What's wrong with you?

04:52.120 --> 04:53.920
               Shhh!

04:53.920 --> 04:56.560
         He's a murderer.

04:56.560 --> 04:59.920
Great.
These pyjamas have holes in them.

04:59.920 --> 05:01.160
          Call the nurse.

05:01.160 --> 05:03.160
How?

05:03.160 --> 05:07.160
   Push that button over there.

05:16.160 --> 05:19.040
I was wondering if...

05:19.040 --> 05:23.040
Let's go.
Careful here. Coming through.

05:27.160 --> 05:30.720
Where's the code?

05:30.720 --> 05:33.640
All right, who's the wise guy?

05:33.640 --> 05:37.640
               Him.

05:41.360 --> 05:43.160
 Ehrlich is supposed to assist me

05:43.160 --> 05:45.640
on a valve replacement in
20 minutes. Have you seen him?

05:45.640 --> 05:48.360
He called earlier today,
this morning, and said he

05:48.360 --> 05:50.240
had to go out of town unexpectedly.

05:50.240 --> 05:53.840
# With a nick nack paddy whack,
 give a dog a bone

05:53.840 --> 05:55.800
# This old man came rolling home.

05:55.800 --> 05:58.960
Daniel, I have been thinking
about the hospital being sold.

05:58.960 --> 06:01.560
Don't know why, but these
old nursery rhymes have

06:01.560 --> 06:03.400
been running through
my head all morning.

06:03.400 --> 06:05.320
Now that Boston General has passed...

06:05.320 --> 06:08.320
Nick nack paddy whack?
What is the poem intended to mean?

06:08.320 --> 06:12.120
Instead of waiting for the city
to palm us off on God knows who,

06:12.120 --> 06:15.160
we should be actively looking
for a buyer we can live with.

06:15.160 --> 06:18.560
I agree.
Some group with a large cash flow,

06:18.560 --> 06:21.080
rooted in humanitarian goals.

06:21.080 --> 06:23.080
An organisation that has withstood

06:23.080 --> 06:26.520
crusades, reformations,
inquisitions.

06:26.520 --> 06:28.960
Yes, well, while you're
talking to the Elks Club,

06:28.960 --> 06:30.520
  I want to pursue my own angle.

06:30.520 --> 06:33.080
Hickory dickory dock,
   the mouse ran up the clock,

06:33.080 --> 06:35.120
the clock struck one,
     the mouse ran down. Why?

06:35.120 --> 06:39.120
Maybe he got tired of talking to you.

06:39.400 --> 06:43.400
# With a nick nack paddy whack,
 give the dog a bone. #

06:44.160 --> 06:45.960
      The square root of 64,

06:45.960 --> 06:49.960
minus the square
of two plus six,

06:51.520 --> 06:53.720
          divided by two,

06:53.720 --> 06:57.720
and the angle of the dangle is five.

06:58.040 --> 06:59.960
         I hate homework.

06:59.960 --> 07:02.600
They took a lot of blood.

07:02.600 --> 07:05.280
Yeah, the local vampires
here take it from everyone.

07:05.280 --> 07:07.520
         What's your name?

07:07.520 --> 07:08.600
Ryan.

07:08.600 --> 07:12.400
Elvis.
My mom freaked over Elvis Presley.

07:12.400 --> 07:14.280
I don't mind being named after him,

07:14.280 --> 07:18.280
because I hear before he was a fat
greaser, he got lots of women.

07:26.640 --> 07:27.640
Elvis?

07:27.640 --> 07:30.920
I'm Doctor Novino.

07:30.920 --> 07:32.680
Here to take you down
for your bone scan.

07:32.680 --> 07:34.400
               Wow.

07:34.400 --> 07:38.400
Into the wheelchair.

07:42.080 --> 07:46.080
    You've got ravishing eyes.

07:49.400 --> 07:53.400
     Great start, you...dork.

07:55.600 --> 07:59.600
Hey, what's your name?

08:03.120 --> 08:07.000
I'm so out of touch, you know. I
have no idea what you've been doing.

08:07.000 --> 08:10.080
After the Navy, I started
a construction outfit.

08:10.080 --> 08:13.480
I lost that business and
a couple of others along the way.

08:13.480 --> 08:16.120
Now I'm a ground foreman for
a big contractor in the city.

08:16.120 --> 08:18.000
So how is it you
managed to keep your hair?

08:18.000 --> 08:20.240
          Lucky, I guess.

08:20.240 --> 08:21.400
Been married long?

08:21.400 --> 08:23.120
         Second time. You?

08:23.120 --> 08:25.520
My wife died.

08:25.520 --> 08:28.680
Haven't been able
to find anyone else.

08:28.680 --> 08:31.600
Plenty of those around.
Just got to look. Kids?

08:31.600 --> 08:33.400
Yeah, two. Daughter and son.

08:33.400 --> 08:34.600
        How old's your boy?

08:34.600 --> 08:37.000
Tommy's 10. No, he's 11.

08:37.000 --> 08:38.679
 About the same age you and I were

08:38.679 --> 08:42.679
when we stole old man
Milton's pocket watch.

08:43.080 --> 08:45.920
I can him see now laying
up in that barber chair

08:45.920 --> 08:49.160
with a towel over his fat face.
Perfect set-up, wasn't it?

08:49.160 --> 08:53.160
You distracted Sean
and I lifted that pocket watch

08:53.200 --> 08:56.440
right out of his vest pocket.
Got away clean.

08:56.440 --> 08:58.080
God, it was beautiful.

08:58.080 --> 09:01.240
All solid gold and engraved,
with that long gold fob.

09:01.240 --> 09:04.120
You and I sat there for hours,
staring at the damn thing.

09:04.120 --> 09:06.560
Thought we'd get
caught if we pawned it.

09:06.560 --> 09:09.480
Then we buried it in an old
coffee can out in the park.

09:09.480 --> 09:11.280
Our time capsule.

09:11.280 --> 09:12.920
            Our secret.

09:12.920 --> 09:15.600
Dr Westphall, I have
these lab reports for you.

09:15.600 --> 09:16.440
Can't it wait, Elliot?

09:16.440 --> 09:20.440
Can't it wait, Elliot?
I thought you might
want to see this.

09:24.200 --> 09:25.880
OK, thank you, Elliot.

09:25.880 --> 09:26.880
Yes, sir.

09:26.880 --> 09:30.080
      Big man at St Eligius.

09:30.080 --> 09:31.360
        Is something wrong?

09:31.360 --> 09:34.120
Ryan's lab reports.

09:34.120 --> 09:36.960
It's what I suspected when
you brought him in, George.

09:36.960 --> 09:40.960
I don't want you to panic.

09:41.160 --> 09:45.160
Your boy has diabetes.

09:46.040 --> 09:47.960
     Still don't remember me?

09:47.960 --> 09:49.720
     Still don't remember me?
I'm sorry.

09:49.720 --> 09:53.240
I visited you on the day you
were artificially inseminated.

09:53.240 --> 09:57.240
    I left you a savings bond.

09:58.360 --> 10:01.480
Oh, yeah. My husband and I
   could never figure out why.

10:01.480 --> 10:04.440
It's hospital policy -
every hundredth patient

10:04.440 --> 10:06.680
     gets a share of America.

10:06.680 --> 10:09.120
    What'd the ultrasound show?

10:09.120 --> 10:11.800
Melissa, you and the baby
are going to be fine. But...

10:11.800 --> 10:13.400
               But?

10:13.400 --> 10:16.920
You went into false labour. I'd like
to keep you for another day or two.

10:16.920 --> 10:18.960
    How dilated is the cervix?

10:18.960 --> 10:22.560
Sometimes false labour
can trigger the real thing.

10:22.560 --> 10:23.240
Oh, no.

10:23.240 --> 10:24.840
   It's nothing to worry about.

10:24.840 --> 10:26.040
Can I see you in the hallway?

10:26.040 --> 10:27.520
               Sure.

10:27.520 --> 10:29.560
        I'll be right back.

10:29.560 --> 10:32.760
Somehow I knew you'd say that.

10:32.760 --> 10:35.040
I looked on the chart,
      and her records,

10:35.040 --> 10:39.040
and I didn't see your name
associated with this case anywhere.

10:41.560 --> 10:44.440
My involvement with the
Tillmans is confidential.

10:44.440 --> 10:45.920
Come on, Fiscus, the truth.

10:45.920 --> 10:49.920
                OK.

10:51.840 --> 10:53.200
Wayne-o!

10:53.200 --> 10:54.520
         Beat it, Elliot.

10:54.520 --> 10:56.520
Hey, I just laid down.

10:56.520 --> 10:59.400
             Get out.

10:59.400 --> 11:03.400
OK!

11:09.360 --> 11:13.240
Nine months ago,
I was engaged to be married.

11:13.240 --> 11:14.920
       That's not important.

11:14.920 --> 11:18.280
  Caldwell had just gotten AIDS.

11:18.280 --> 11:22.080
     But that's not important.

11:22.080 --> 11:24.280
I had my semen
freeze-dried for posterity,

11:24.280 --> 11:26.640
    left it in the sperm bank.

11:26.640 --> 11:27.800
Oh, yeah, I remember.

11:27.800 --> 11:30.440
  By mistake it got inseminated.

11:30.440 --> 11:31.520
In Mrs Tillman.

11:31.520 --> 11:35.520
               Yep.

11:36.560 --> 11:40.560
Ever since I died,
I've had this amorphous memory

11:40.560 --> 11:44.560
of talking to the mirror
about things I hadn't done yet -

11:45.320 --> 11:47.040
          having a child.

11:47.040 --> 11:50.440
You've got a family.
You take it for granted.

11:50.440 --> 11:52.320
I'm not even close
to being married now.

11:52.320 --> 11:56.320
The next time I die,
I'm afraid it's gonna be forever.

11:56.520 --> 12:00.160
So this child may be my only legacy.

12:00.160 --> 12:02.160
Powerful stuff.

12:02.160 --> 12:03.960
     You understand my crisis?

12:03.960 --> 12:07.120
No, I'm talking about your protein.

12:07.120 --> 12:09.280
Mrs Tillman.

12:09.280 --> 12:13.280
She's gonna have twins.

12:14.960 --> 12:16.360
That hurt?

12:16.360 --> 12:18.040
             A little.

12:18.040 --> 12:19.520
Police dog got you pretty good.

12:19.520 --> 12:21.160
             Doberman.

12:21.160 --> 12:23.320
OK, we just have to
wrap this all over again.

12:23.320 --> 12:26.960
The ER report from last
night said you got injured

12:26.960 --> 12:29.280
trying to rob a liquor store.

12:29.280 --> 12:31.720
The other guy they brought in
with you got shot in the throat.

12:31.720 --> 12:34.000
  You know what happened to him?

12:34.000 --> 12:36.200
No, only that he was
taken in for surgery.

12:36.200 --> 12:38.640
Guess you'll get a couple of months

12:38.640 --> 12:42.200
in a juvenile detention centre
  for this.

12:42.200 --> 12:46.200
You know, when I was 14,
I was running for student council,

12:46.320 --> 12:50.320
trying out for the
cross-country team.

12:50.400 --> 12:54.400
Never mind.

12:55.200 --> 12:56.720
You robbed a liquor store?!

12:56.720 --> 12:58.960
               Yeah.

12:58.960 --> 13:00.480
What are they going to do to you?

13:00.480 --> 13:03.200
             Nothing.

13:03.200 --> 13:04.200
I'd be scared.

13:04.200 --> 13:06.720
             Figures.

13:06.720 --> 13:08.000
Can I ask you another question?

13:08.000 --> 13:10.920
                No.

13:10.920 --> 13:12.400
Get in bed, son.

13:12.400 --> 13:16.400
Ryan, we have to talk.

13:23.280 --> 13:27.280
          Hang in there.

13:31.160 --> 13:35.160
Carol - nice name!

13:45.680 --> 13:49.680
The bone scan will help us
locate the source of your infection.

13:49.680 --> 13:52.240
What do you listen to on that thing?

13:52.240 --> 13:53.280
The classics.

13:53.280 --> 13:54.600
        Beethoven, Mozart?

13:54.600 --> 13:57.680
The Beastie Boys!

13:57.680 --> 14:00.000
Listen, you just lie there
and don't move.

14:00.000 --> 14:03.680
Once the radioactive dye
has been absorbed by your bones,

14:03.680 --> 14:05.800
somebody will take you
down for a scan.

14:05.800 --> 14:08.640
And then I'll meet you in a few
hours, once you're finished, OK?

14:08.640 --> 14:12.120
Do you have that deal where if
a kid finds that he's really sick,

14:12.120 --> 14:13.640
he can get what he wants most?

14:13.640 --> 14:16.480
Yes, we have a Grant A Dream
programme.

14:16.480 --> 14:20.480
Good.

14:21.920 --> 14:24.520
        Under the B, nine.

14:24.520 --> 14:25.680
I don't have time for all this.

14:25.680 --> 14:27.200
I don't have time for all this.
   Nonsense, you paid your buck.

14:27.200 --> 14:30.880
Monsignor, you're director
    of medical operations

14:30.880 --> 14:32.440
for the archdiocese.

14:32.440 --> 14:34.200
You've got to be able to help us.

14:34.200 --> 14:36.560
         Under the N, 33.

14:36.560 --> 14:38.320
The church built the hospital.

14:38.320 --> 14:40.600
I can't fathom you'd let it
fall into the wrong hands.

14:40.600 --> 14:43.760
We sold it to the city.
What could be worse than that?

14:43.760 --> 14:47.760
     Made a pretty penny, too.

14:47.960 --> 14:51.440
I'm trying to patch together
a quilt, a consortium of all

14:51.440 --> 14:54.880
the religious leaders of the area,
to get them to put pressure on their

14:54.880 --> 14:57.960
denominations to come
through with large...

14:57.960 --> 14:59.240
denominations.

14:59.240 --> 15:01.640
         Under the O, 69.

15:01.640 --> 15:03.240
Can I count on you, Monsignor?

15:03.240 --> 15:06.200
You don't have a prayer.
I've been raising money for

15:06.200 --> 15:07.880
the Catholic Church for 40 years now.

15:07.880 --> 15:11.880
Come back here every week where I
began, raising nickels and dimes.

15:12.680 --> 15:15.000
     Frankly, Dr Auschlander,

15:15.000 --> 15:17.800
the charitable climate has become
so complex,

15:17.800 --> 15:19.600
   what with the new tax reforms

15:19.600 --> 15:23.080
and the severe drop
in churches' enrolment...

15:23.080 --> 15:26.600
I'm sorry, I just can't help you out.

15:26.600 --> 15:29.880
Our hospital was named
after one of your saints.

15:29.880 --> 15:33.880
How will he feel looking down from
heaven when the place is converted

15:33.880 --> 15:35.840
into condos for yuppies?

15:35.840 --> 15:39.840
I remember attending the
original dedication ceremony.

15:41.520 --> 15:43.680
You think there's life
in the old gal yet, huh?

15:43.680 --> 15:46.160
Absolutely.
  But what's more important is,

15:46.160 --> 15:50.160
we can't take the risk
  of finding out if I am wrong.

15:53.840 --> 15:55.560
               I 19.

15:55.560 --> 15:57.520
    I'll talk to the Cardinal.

15:57.520 --> 15:58.800
    I'll talk to the Cardinal.
Bingo.

15:58.800 --> 16:00.040
        Well, it's a start.

16:00.040 --> 16:04.040
No, I win. Bingo!

16:05.440 --> 16:09.440
This is what a syringe looks like.

16:09.720 --> 16:11.840
How long will I have
to take the shots?

16:11.840 --> 16:13.360
        Rest of your life.

16:13.360 --> 16:15.400
Do you get used to it?

16:15.400 --> 16:18.000
       Yeah. After a while.

16:18.000 --> 16:22.000
What I want you to do now
is practise, all right?

16:22.000 --> 16:24.600
 Now, pretend this is your thigh.

16:24.600 --> 16:26.200
  You put the needle in quickly.

16:26.200 --> 16:29.080
Like that.
Pull the plunger.

16:29.080 --> 16:31.520
Make sure there's no blood in there.

16:31.520 --> 16:34.960
Then you push the plunger all the
way down and pull the needle out.

16:34.960 --> 16:35.960
            That's it.

16:35.960 --> 16:38.280
What if I don't have the shots?

16:38.280 --> 16:40.840
Ryan, diabetes
is a very dangerous disease

16:40.840 --> 16:44.840
unless you take
these treatments.

16:48.360 --> 16:49.360
I won't be able to.

16:49.360 --> 16:52.720
 Plenty of time. There's no rush.

16:52.720 --> 16:56.640
Come on, give it a try, Tiger.

16:56.640 --> 17:00.640
I'll see you later.

17:02.360 --> 17:03.600
Damn it!

17:03.600 --> 17:07.240
George, he's gonna be fine. Stabilise
his blood sugar and teach him

17:07.240 --> 17:11.240
how to give himself those insulin
injections and you can take him home.

17:11.680 --> 17:14.079
My baby boy.

17:14.079 --> 17:17.920
Look, why don't we go out and have a
beer later? Something to eat? On me!

17:17.920 --> 17:19.480
It's a good idea.

17:19.480 --> 17:23.480
I'll call the wife.

17:23.599 --> 17:24.839
    I know how to drive a car.

17:24.839 --> 17:28.840
Uh-huh? OK, out you go.

17:29.080 --> 17:30.880
          See you, Carol.

17:30.880 --> 17:34.880
See ya.

17:35.080 --> 17:39.080
OK, lights out, the show's over.

17:40.120 --> 17:44.120
You, get some sleep.
It'll all be over tomorrow.

17:46.360 --> 17:50.360
OK, good night.

17:50.920 --> 17:53.960
And I mean it!

17:53.960 --> 17:57.960
     I think Carol's into me.

17:59.240 --> 18:01.280
    What you doing, Rye Bread?

18:01.280 --> 18:02.760
Prayers.

18:02.760 --> 18:04.560
           Kidding?!  No.

